re $$ The Maclaurin\'s series for (1+x)^n, up to and including x^3:;$$\\begin{align} y\\approx 1+ nx + \\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}x^2+\\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}x^3 \\end{align}$$;;(ii);$$ \\therefore $$ Expansion of $$ (4-x)^{\\frac{3}{2}(1+2x^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}} }$$ up to and including $$x^3$$;$$\\begin{align} = 4^{\\frac{3}{2}}\\left(1-\\frac{x}{4}\\right)^{\\frac{3}{2}}(1+2x^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}};\\\\ \\approx 8\\left[1+\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\left(-\\frac{x}{4}\\right)\\right)+\\frac{\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)}{2!}\\left(-\\frac{x}{4}\\right)^2+\\frac{\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)\\left(-\\frac{1}{2}\\right)}{3!}\\left(-\\frac{x}{4}^3\\right)\\right]\\left[1+3x^2\\right];\\\\ = 3\\left(1-\\frac{3x}{8}+\\frac{3x^2}{128}+\\frac{x^3}{1024}\\right)\\left(1+3x^2\\right);\\\\ = \\left(8-3x+\\frac{3x^2}{16}+\\frac{x^3}{128}\\right)\\left(1+3x^2\\right);\\\\ \\approx 8 - 3x +\\left(\\frac{3}{16}+24\\right)x^2 + \\left(\\frac{1}{128}-9\\right)x^3;\\\\ = 8 - 3x + \\frac{387}{16}x^2-\\frac{1153}{128}x^3\\end{align}$$;;(iii);$$\\therefore$$ For expansion in part (ii) to be valid, $$\\left|\\frac{x}{4}\\right| < 1$$ and $$\\left|2x^2\\right| < 1$$.;$$\\begin{align} \\left|\\frac{x}{4}\\right| < 1 \\Rightarrow -4 < x <4;\\\\;\\\\ \\left|2x^2\\right| < 1 \\Rightarrow 2x^2 - 1 < 0;\\\\ x^2-\\frac{1}{2} < 0 \\Rightarrow \\left(x-\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\right)\\left(x+\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\right)<0;\\\\ \\Rightarrow -\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} < x < \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The set of values of $$x = \\left\\{x \\in \\mathbb{R}: -\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} < x < \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\right\\}$$'),(292,'200704003004','(i) ;$$\\therefore$$ The exact value of $$\\int^{\\frac{2}{3}\\pi}_{0} \\sin^{2}{x} \\space dx$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{2}{3}\\pi}_{0} \\frac{1-\\cos{2x}}{2} \\space dx \\space (Use \\space \\cos{2x} = 1-2\\sin^{2} x);\\\\ = \\left[\\frac{x}{2} - \\frac{\\sin{2x}}{4}\\right]^{\\frac{2}{3}\\pi}_{0};\\\\ = \\frac{5\\pi}{6} - \\frac{\\sin{\\frac{10\\pi}{3}}}{4};\\\\ = \\frac{5}{6}\\pi + \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8}\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The exact value of $$\\int^{\\frac{5}{3}\\pi}_{0} \\cos^{2}{x} \\space dx$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{5}{3}\\pi}_{0} (1-\\sin^{2}{x}) \\space dx;\\\\ = \\left[x\\right]^{\\frac{5}{3}\\pi}_{0} - \\frac{5\\pi}{6} - \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8};\\\\ = \\frac{5\\pi}{3} - \\frac{5\\pi}{6} - \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8};\\\\ = \\frac{5}{6}\\pi - \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8}\\end{align}$$;;(ii);The shaded region R is bounded by the curve $$y=x^2\\sin{x}$$, the line $$x=\\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$ and the part of the x-axis between 0  and $$\\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$ as shown.;img;;a);$$\\therefore$$ The exact area of R;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} x^2\\sin{x} \\space dx;\\\\ = \\left[(-\\cos{x})x^2\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} - \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0}(-\\cos{x})(2x) \\space dx;\\\\ = 0 + \\left[(\\sin{x})(2x)\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} - \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} 2\\sin{x}\\space dx;\\\\ = \\pi + \\left[2\\cos{x}\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} ;\\\\ = \\pi + (0-2) ;\\\\ = \\pi - 2 \\space units^2\\end{align}$$;;b) ;The bounded region R is made to rotate completely about the x-axis;$$\\therefore$$ The numerical value of volume of revolution;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}_{0} \\pi y^2 \\space dx = \\int^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}_{0} \\pi (x^4\\sin^{2}{x}) \\space dx;\\\\ = 5.391 \\space units^3 \\space (from \\space GC) (3dp)\\end{align}$$'),(293,'200704003005','(i);$$\\therefore$$ Real life example of a situation in which quota sampling could be used:;Quota sampling could be used by a market researcher to conduct a survey about how frequently shoppers at a particular mall visit the mall. A sample of 100 shoppers, subdivided according to age group or gender.;;Quota sampling is appropriate in this situation because it is quick and convenient to carry out, since the tasks of listing the whole population, randomly selecting the sample and following-up on non-respondents can be omitted from the process.;;Disadvantages of quota sampling:;Quota sampling is a non-random sampling method selection that is biased as those selected will be those who are most willing to cooperate.;The issue of the sample not representative of the general population leading to faulty conclusions remains a difficult problem;;(ii);$$\\therefore$$ Based on the situation described in part(i), stratified sampling cannot be used because the sampling frame is not accessible'),(294,'200704003006','Let X represent the number of people who have gene A out of a random sample of 10 $$\\Rightarrow$$ X ~ B(10,0.24);;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that our of 10, at most 4 have gene A;$$\\begin{align} = P(X \\leq 4);\\\\ = P(X=0) + P(X=1) + P(X=2) + P(X=3) + P(X=4);\\\\ = \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\0\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^0(0.76)^{10} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\1\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^1(0.76)^{9} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\2\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^2(0.76)^{8} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\3\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^3(0.76)^{7} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\4\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^4(0.76)^{6};\\\\ = 0.06428 + 0.20301 + 0.28849 + 0.24294 + 0.13425;\\\\ = 0.93297;\\\\ = 0.933 (3dp)(or \\space straight \\space from \\space GC)\\end{align}$$;;Another random sample of 1000 from the population is taken.;Using the appropriate approximations,;(i);Let Y represent the no. of people who have gene A out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ Y ~ B(1000,0.24);Since n = 1000 is large, np = 240 > 5 and n(1-p) = 760 > 5, Y ~ N(240,182.4) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that between 230 and 260, inclusive have gene A;$$\\begin{align} = P(230 leq Y leq 260);\\\\ = P(229.5 leq Y \\leq 260.5) \\space (continuity \\space correction);\\\\ = P\\left(\\frac{229.5-240}{\\sqrt{182.4}} \\leq Z \\leq \\frac{260.5-240}{\\sqrt{182.4}}\\right);\\\\ = P(-0.7775 \\leq Z \\leq 1.15179);\\\\ = \\Phi(1.518)-[1-\\Phi(0.778)];\\\\ = 0.9355-[1-0.7817];\\\\ = 0.7172 = 0.717(3dp)\\end{align}$$;;(ii) ;Let u represent the number of people who have gene B out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ U ~ B(1000,.003);Since n=1000 is large and np = 3<10, U ~ Po(3) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that at least 2 but fewer than 5 have gene B;$$\\begin{align} = P(2 \\leq U < 5);\\\\ = P(U=2) + P(U=3) + P(U=4);\\\\ = e^{-3}\\left[\\frac{(3)^2}{2!}+\\frac{(3)^3}{3!} + \\frac{(3)^4}{4!}\\right];\\\\ = 0.616(3dp)\\end{align}$$'),(295,'200704003007','Let X represent the time in hours taken by a student to complete a project, with population mean $$\\mu$$.;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of mean, $$\\mu$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{4626}{150} = 30.84\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of population variance, $$s^2$$;$$\\begin{align} =\\frac{1}{150-1}\\left[147691-\\frac{4626^2}{150}\\right];\\\\ = \\frac{5025.16}{149} = 33.7(3sf) \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ To test if the population mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30 hours at 5% significance level,;Test $$H_0: \\mu = 30$$ against $$H_1:\\mu>30$$;One-tail test at 5% significance level, $$\\alpha = 0.05$$;Under $$H_0$$, since $$n=150$$ is large, by Central Limit Theorem, $$\\overline{X} ~ N(30, \\frac{33.7}{150})$$ approximately, where $$\\overline{X}$$ is the sample means.;Perform Z-test with: $$\\mu_0 = 30, s = \\sqrt{33.7259}, \\overline{x} = 30.84$$ and $$n=150$$.;From GC, p-value = 0.0382;Since p-value = 0.0382 < 0.05, we reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that there is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level that the mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30hours.;;$$\\therefore$$ No assumption is needed in order for the test to be valid because since sample size is large, by Central Limit Theorem, the sample mean is approximately normally distributed.'),(296,'200704003008','(i) ;Let C and T represent mass of a randomly chosen chicken and turkey respectively, in kg $$\\Rightarrow \\space C \\sim N(2.2,0.5^2), T\\sim N